  "informal_statement": "Reflecting a point (x, y) over the x-axis to (x, -y) preserves its squared distance to any point (qx, 0) lying on the x-axis, since the point's y-coordinate is baked into the statement as 0 and y^2 = (-y)^2.",
  "informal_proof_idea": "The (x - qx)^2 term is shared; the reflected term differs only by squaring y versus -y, which are equal squares. `ring` closes it as an unconditional polynomial identity (the y-coordinate of the axis point is already fixed at 0 in the statement, so no hypothesis is needed).",
  "formal_statement_pp": "theorem reflection_over_x_axis (x y qx : ℝ) : (x - qx) ^ 2 + y ^ 2 = (x - qx) ^ 2 + (-y) ^ 2",
